# Specific:


# General:
Dimensions are a combination of a numeric value, a unit for the value, and a classification as to what sort of value it is. They can be measured on the entity by some means, such as counting or using an instrument. The data structure is commonly used for physical things (e.g. height and width), but is also applicable to textual works (e.g. number of words) or even people (e.g. height, weight). If there is a countable feature, then that can be expressed as a dimension using this data structure. See: https://linked.art/api/1.0/shared/dimension/ and https://linked.art/model/object/physical/#dimensions

# Specific:


# General:
The resource that references this assignment was assigned to its parent resource by this activity. This is especially useful for distinguishing the context of when a piece of data was known or asserted, for example when a measurement took place or the organization that assigned an identifier. For example, a dimension of an object was assigned by the activity that measured the object, carried out by the curator (or other), or the accession number of the object was assigned to it by the registrar.

If there is a countable feature, then that can be expressed as a dimension using this data structure.
